  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (US)\n- First international recognition of money laundering as a financial crime\n- Initial reporting requirements for financial institutions\n\n2. 1980s-1990s\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) established in 1989\n- International cooperation and standard-setting\n- Expanded legal frameworks for detecting and preventing money laundering\n\n3. Key Milestones\n- 1990 US Money Laundering Control Act\n- 2001 USA PATRIOT Act\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Increased penalties\n- Expanded scope of financial investigations\n\n4. Modern Developments\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Enhanced due diligence requirements\n- Cryptocurrency transaction monitoring\n- Beneficial ownership transparency rules\n\n5. Global Trends\n- Comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- International information sharing\n- Risk-based compliance approaches\n- Advanced technological monitoring systems\n\n6. Recent Innovations\n- Blockchain tracking\n- Artificial intelligence for suspicious activity detection\n- Cross-border regulatory collaboration\n\nThe legislation continues to adapt to emerging financial technologies and global financial crime trends.",
